                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@Zaibis: The rationale I like to use for most places rule applies that in theory a mutli-processor platform could implement something like &lt;code&gt;A=B=5;&lt;/code&gt; as &quot;Write-lock A; Write-Lock B; Store 5 to A; store 5 to B; Unlock B; Unock A;&quot;, and a statement like &lt;code&gt;C=A+B;&lt;/code&gt; as &quot;Read-lock A; Read-lock B; Compute A+B; Unlock A and B; Write-lock C; Store result; Unlock C;&quot;.  That would ensure that if one thread did &lt;code&gt;A=B=5;&lt;/code&gt; while another did &lt;code&gt;C=A+B;&lt;/code&gt; the latter thread would either see both writes as having taken place or neither.  Potentially a useful guarantee.  If one thread did &lt;code&gt;I=I=5;&lt;/code&gt;, however, ...&lt;/span&gt;

