            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;... and the compiler didn&apos;t notice that both writes were to the same location (if one or both lvalues involve pointers, that may be hard to determine), the generated code could deadlock. I don&apos;t think any real-world implementations implement such locking as part of their normal behavior, but it would be permissible under the standard, and if hardware could implement such behaviors cheaply it might be useful.  On today&apos;s hardware such behavior would be way too expensive to implement as a default, but that doesn&apos;t mean it would always be thus.&lt;/span&gt;

